================================================================================
Cortex-A53 execution testbench README
================================================================================

The Cortex-A53 Configuration and Signoff Guide documents how to set up and
run the Cortex-A53 execution testbench.  This README file contains supplementary
information in the form of examples to show how you can install the
dependencies required to run certain parts of the testbench.

This README file is split into two sections:

  Section 1: describes how to install Protocol Buffers which are required to
             generate Tarmac instruction trace when running the tests.

  Section 2: describes how to install a compatible GCC toolchain that you
             can use if you want to re-compile any of the supplied tests


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SECTION 1: Installing Protocol Buffers
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

If you want to enable Tarmac instruction trace when running tests in the
execution testbench, you must first install Protocol Buffers.  The following
package is required:

  1. Google Protocol Buffers 2.4.1
       Web:          https://code.google.com/p/protobuf
       Package name: protobuf-2.4.1.tar.bz2

You must build and install a 32-bit version of the protocol buffers regardless
of whether you are running 32-bit or 64-bit simulations.  After you have
downloaded and extracted the protocol buffers package, you can configure and
install using the following commands from the protocol buffers source directory:

  $ ./configure --with-zlib --prefix=/path/to/install/root CXX='g++ -m32'
  $ make install



--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SECTION 2: Installing GCC toolchains
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

All tests in the execution testbench are provided with pre-compiled ELF files
and memory initialization files.  It is therefore not necessary to re-compile
the tests unless you modify the source code.

If you do re-compile the tests, or if you write any new tests, you must use a
version of GCC that supports the ARMv8 architecture.  In GCC support for the
ARMv8 architecture is split between two separate toolchains: one which supports
AArch32 and one which supports AArch64.  Both toolchains are required to compile
all of the execution testbench tests.

The toolchains must be built for 'baremetal' targets, because the execution
testbench tests contain standalone code that does not require an operating
system.

ARM recommends that you:

 - use Linaro GCC toolchains, see http://www.linaro.org

 - compile your own toolchains from source, in order to create a toolchain for
   the correct target

The headings below contain examples to show how you can build a compatible GCC
toolchain from source.


----------------
Required sources
----------------

The following source packages are required and can be downloaded from the
websites indicated.

  1. Linaro GCC 4.9, 2014.06-1 release
       Web:     http://releases.linaro.org/14.06/components/toolchain/gcc-linaro/4.9
       Package: gcc-linaro-4.9-2014.06-1.tar.xz

  2. Linaro Newlib 2.1.0, 2014.02 release
       Web:     http://releases.linaro.org/14.02/components/toolchain/newlib-linaro
       Package: newlib-linaro-2.1.0-2014.02.tar.bz2

  3. Linaro Binutils 2.24.0, 2014.06 release
       Web:     http://releases.linaro.org/14.06/components/toolchain/binutils-linaro
       Package: binutils-linaro-2.24.0-2014.06.tar.bz2


Note: ARM has tested the execution testbench using the tool versions above.
      Other tool versions might be supported but have not been tested.


-----------------------------------------
Prerequisites for building the toolchains
-----------------------------------------

To build the ARM GCC tools your host workstation must have a native version of
GCC installed and set up correctly.


-----------------------
Building the toolchains
-----------------------

Two target toolchains must be built:

  1. arm-none-eabi         (armeb-none-eabi for big-endian)
  2. aarch64-none-elf      (aarch64_be-none-elf for big-endian)

The first target toolchain is used to compile AArch32 code and the second is
used to compile AArch64 code.  Both of these toolchains can be built from the
same GCC, Newlib and Binutils sources.

The commands below can be used as a guide for building the toolchains.  This set
of commands must be run twice - once for the arm-none-eabi target and once for
the aarch64-none-elf target.

In the following commands substitute:
  <target>      with the current target, e.g. arm-none-eabi
  <install_dir> with your preferred tools installation directory (absolute path)

The example commands assume that you are using the tool versions listed under
the "Required sources" heading in this README and that you have saved these
files to your desired build directory.

In the following example commands the '\' character is used to break up long
lines.  When writing these commands you can join the lines together and omit the
'\' character.

  1. Extract the sources

       $ tar Jxf gcc-linaro-4.9-2014.06-1.tar.xz
       $ tar jxf newlib-linaro-2.1.0-2014.02.tar.bz2
       $ tar jxf binutils-linaro-2.24.0-2014.06.tar.bz2

  2. Download GCC prerequisites.

       $ cd gcc-linaro-4.9-2014.06-1
       $ ./contrib/download_prerequisites
       $ cd ..

  3. Make build directories.

       $ mkdir -p build-<target>/binutils
       $ mkdir -p build-<target>/gcc_stage1
       $ mkdir -p build-<target>/gcc_stage2
       $ mkdir -p build-<target>/newlib

  4. Configure, build and install binutils.

       $ cd build-<target>/binutils
       $ ../../binutils-linaro-2.24.0-2014.06/configure --target=<target>                     \
                                                        --prefix=<install_dir>                \
                                                        --with-sysroot=<install_dir>/<target> \
                                                        --disable-werror
       $ make all-binutils all-gas all-ld
       $ make install-binutils install-gas install-ld
       $ cd ../..

  5. Configure, build and install ARM GCC stage 1.  This step creates a
     bootstrap ARM toolchain without any of the standard C libraries. Note that
     in the following commands any text within square brackets must only be used
     when building the arm-none-eabi (or armeb-none-eabi) toolchain.  
     You do not type the square brackets themselves, only the text between them.

       $ cd build-<target>/gcc_stage1
       $ ../../gcc-linaro-4.9-2014.06-1/configure --target=<target>                     \
                                                  --prefix=<install_dir>                \
                                                  --with-sysroot=<install_dir>/<target> \
                                                  --with-arch=armv8-a+crc               \
                                                  --with-cpu=cortex-a53                 \
                                                  [--with-fpu=crypto-neon-fp-armv8]     \
                                                  --disable-werror                      \
                                                  --enable-languages=c                  \
                                                  --disable-shared                      \
                                                  --disable-threads                     \
                                                  --without-headers                     \
                                                  --with-newlib                         \
                                                  --with-gnu-as                         \
                                                  --with-gnu-ld
       $ make all-gcc
       $ make install-gcc
       $ cd ../..

  6. Add the new GCC toolchain to your PATH so that it can be found during the
     next setup stages.

     If you are using a Bourne shell or equivalent:
       $ PATH="<install_dir>/bin:$PATH"

     If you are using a C-shell or equivalent:
       $ setenv PATH "<install_dir>/bin:$PATH"

  7. Configure, build and install Newlib using the bootstrap ARM compiler.
     Note that in the following commands any text within square brackets must only be used
     when building the big-endian toolchain (for armeb-none-eabi or aarch64_be-none-elf target).  
     You do not type the square brackets themselves, only the text between them.

       $ cd build-<target>/newlib
       $ ../../newlib-linaro-2.1.0-2014.02/configure --target=<target>                     \
                                                     --prefix=<install_dir>                \
                                                     --with-sysroot=<install_dir>/<target> \
                                                     --disable-werror                      \
                                                     --enable-newlib-io-long-long          \
                                                     CFLAGS_FOR_TARGET="-D__ARM_ARCH_7A__ [-mbig-endian -g -O2]"
       $ make all-target-newlib all-target-libgloss
       $ make install-target-newlib install-target-libgloss

     Note: you might need to run the above command for a second time, if the
           first invocation exits with an error.

       $ cd ../..

  8. Configure, build and install ARM GCC stage 2.  This step creates the final
     ARM toolchain that includes the libraries that were built in the previous
     step. Note that in the following commands any text within square brackets
     must only be used when building the arm-none-eabi (or armeb-none-eabi) toolchain.  
     You do not type the square brackets themselves, only the text between them.

       $ cd build-<target>/gcc_stage2
       $ ../../gcc-linaro-4.9-2014.06-1/configure --target=<target>                     \
                                                  --prefix=<install_dir>                \
                                                  --with-sysroot=<install_dir>/<target> \
                                                  --with-arch=armv8-a+crc               \
                                                  --with-cpu=cortex-a53                 \
                                                  [--with-fpu=crypto-neon-fp-armv8]     \
                                                  --disable-werror                      \
                                                  --enable-languages=c,c++              \
                                                  --disable-shared                      \
                                                  --disable-threads                     \
                                                  --disable-nls                         \
                                                  --disable-tls                         \
                                                  --with-newlib                         \
                                                  --with-gnu-as                         \
                                                  --with-gnu-ld
       $ make all
       $ make install


The resulting GCC toolchain will now be available in your installation
directory, <install_dir>.  You added this directory to your PATH in step 6
above.

If you start a new shell to re-compile the execution testbench code then
you must re-add <install_dir> to the PATH each time, or update your shell
configuration to do this automatically.

